{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489077"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:03:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:03:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"585"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/585"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.84,0.05,0.02,0.08,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"585"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86759"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/585"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"585"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71029"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"185"},{"type":"tags","id":"1887"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"11010"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"263"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2362"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86759","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86759"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 85-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a 12-month history of fatigue and unsteadiness. His wife reports he seems \u0027off colour\u0027. He has a medical history of partial gastrectomy 15 years ago, recently diagnosed type 2 diabetes mellitus (well controlled with diet), and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. He does not take any regular medications. There is no history of weight loss or bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination reveals subtle weakness in all muscle groups of the lower limbs bilaterally, with loss of proprioception and vibration sense equally up to the ankles. Tandem gait is impaired. Monofilament testing is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most likely to be diagnostic?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Serum B12 level","Serum thiamine level","Serum folate level","Nerve conduction studies","Cerebrospinal fluid analysis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms and signs suggestive of combined peripheral neuropathy and posterior column dysfunction. Given his history of partial gastrectomy, the most likely diagnosis is vitamin B12 deficiency. \u003Cstrong\u003ESerum B12 level\u003C/strong\u003E would confirm this diagnosis. Neurological manifestations of B12 deficiency can occur even before haematological changes are evident.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum thiamine level\u003C/strong\u003E would be relevant if Wernicke\u0027s encephalopathy was suspected, which typically presents with confusion, ataxia, and ophthalmoplegia. While thiamine deficiency can also occur after gastric surgery, the pattern of neurological findings here is more consistent with B12 deficiency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum folate level\u003C/strong\u003E deficiency can cause megaloblastic anaemia but does not typically cause neurological manifestations. While folate levels are often checked alongside B12, it would not explain this clinical picture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENerve conduction studies\u003C/strong\u003E might help characterise the neuropathy but would not identify the underlying cause. They would be more useful in cases where the diagnosis is unclear or to monitor disease progression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECerebrospinal fluid analysis\u003C/strong\u003E would be unnecessarily invasive and unlikely to provide diagnostic information in this case. While it might show elevated protein levels in B12 deficiency, this finding is non-specific.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of posterior column signs (loss of proprioception and vibration sense) with peripheral neuropathy is highly characteristic of B12 deficiency. Common causes include reduced absorption (as seen in pernicious anaemia, gastric surgery, or inflammatory bowel disease), reduced dietary intake (strict vegan diet), or increased demand (pregnancy). In this case, the history of partial gastrectomy impairs intrinsic factor production and thus B12 absorption. While his diabetes could potentially cause peripheral neuropathy, the recent onset and good control make this less likely as the primary cause.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vitamin B12 deficiency commonly presents with combined peripheral neuropathy and posterior column signs, particularly after gastric surgery","Neurological manifestations of B12 deficiency can occur without haematological changes","Common causes of B12 deficiency include reduced absorption (gastric surgery, pernicious anaemia) and reduced intake (strict vegan diet)"],"references":["Means RT, Fairfield KM. Clinical Manifestations and diagnosis of vitamin B12 and folate deficiency. In: Tinauer J, Kunins L, editors.;\u200bUpToDate. [Internet]. Waltham (MA): UpToDate Inc; 2021. [updated 2021 Mar 26; cited 2021 Apr 14]. Available from: http://www.uptodate.com/contents/clinical-manifestations-and-diagnosis-of-vitamin-b12-and-folate-deficiency","Shannon C, Gervasoni A, Williams T. The bariatric surgery patient--nutrition considerations. Aust Fam Physician. 2013;42(8):547-552."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71029"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"585"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71029","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/71029"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-24T16:28:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-24T16:29:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"585"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86759"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data"